spark sql engine in spark | Lec-8



Q1: Catalyst optimizer | Spark SQL engine?
ANS: Catalyst = rule-based query optimizer. Spark SQL engine = compiles SQL/DF to RDD bytecode.
MUST-KNOW: Uses pattern matching & Scala features; whole-stage codegen via Tungsten.

Q2: Why Analysis exception error?
ANS: Table/column/function name not found in Catalog during analysis phase (syntax is fine, resolution fails).
MUST-KNOW: Parser passes, Analyzer fails; check metastore or aliases.

Q3: What is catalog?
ANS: Metadata repository storing databases, tables, views, functions, schemas.
MUST-KNOW: Can be in-memory or external (Hive Metastore, AWS Glue). Session-scoped or persistent.

Q4: Physical planning / Spark Plan?
ANS: Converts optimized logical plan to executable physical plan with specific join strategies, shuffles, partitions.
MUST-KNOW: Uses cost model (stats) to pick best plan; final output = RDD of bytecode.

Q5: Is Spark SQL engine a compiler?
ANS: Yes. Compiles declarative SQL/DF → Java bytecode via Catalyst + Tungsten stages.
MUST-KNOW: Not just interpreter; does whole-stage codegen to avoid virtual function calls.

Q6: Phases to convert code → Java bytecode?
ANS: 4 phases: 1) Parse → 2) Analyze (with Catalog) → 3) Logical Optimize → 4) Physical Plan + CodeGen

FLOW:
SQL/DF → Parse (Unresolved LP) → Analyze (Catalog) → Optimized LP → Physical Plan (Cost Model) → Tungsten CodeGen → Java Bytecode on executors

KEYWORDS: Predicate pushdown, projection pruning, cost-based optimization, whole-stage codegen, unresolved vs resolved plan
